    <section class="py-16 bg-slate-50">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="uppercase text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-8 text-center">Hydrostatic Pressure FAQ</h2>
          
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="bg-white  overflow-hidden border-2 border-slate-600">
              <button class="w-full text-left p-6 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-yellow-500" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
                <div class="flex justify-between items-center">
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900">Can hydrostatic pressure damage my foundation permanently?</h3>
                  <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-cyan-400 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                    <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                  </svg>
                </div>
              </button>
              <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6">
                <p class="text-slate-600">
                  Yes, hydrostatic pressure can cause severe structural damage including foundation heaving, floor cracking, and even foundation failure. The enormous upward force can lift foundations, crack floors, and destabilize your entire home. Early intervention prevents exponentially more expensive structural repairs.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white  overflow-hidden border-2 border-slate-600">
              <button class="w-full text-left p-6 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-yellow-500" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
                <div class="flex justify-between items-center">
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900">Why doesn't exterior waterproofing solve hydrostatic pressure?</h3>
                  <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-cyan-400 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                    <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                  </svg>
                </div>
              </button>
              <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6">
                <p class="text-slate-600">
                  Hydrostatic pressure comes from below your foundation, not from the sides. Exterior waterproofing only addresses lateral water pressure against walls. Floor seepage requires drainage systems that work with the pressure, not against it. Trying to seal against hydrostatic pressure often fails catastrophically.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white  overflow-hidden border-2 border-slate-600">
              <button class="w-full text-left p-6 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-yellow-500" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
                <div class="flex justify-between items-center">
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900">How much does a professional interior drainage system cost?</h3>
                  <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-cyan-400 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                    <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                  </svg>
                </div>
              </button>
              <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6">
                <p class="text-slate-600">
                  Interior drainage systems typically range from $8,000-$15,000 for an average Toronto basement, including sump pump, perimeter drainage, and vapor barriers. While significant, this cost is often less than repairing structural damage from uncontrolled hydrostatic pressure. Many companies offer financing and transferable warranties.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white  overflow-hidden border-2 border-slate-600">
              <button class="w-full text-left p-6 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-yellow-500" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
                <div class="flex justify-between items-center">
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900">Will hydrostatic pressure problems get worse over time?</h3>
                  <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-cyan-400 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                    <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                  </svg>
                </div>
              </button>
              <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6">
                <p class="text-slate-600">
                  Yes, hydrostatic pressure problems almost always worsen over time. Water finds and enlarges weak points, soil conditions change, and climate patterns can increase groundwater levels. What starts as minor seepage often becomes major flooding. The key is addressing the problem before it causes structural damage.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white  overflow-hidden border-2 border-slate-600">
              <button class="w-full text-left p-6 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-yellow-500" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
                <div class="flex justify-between items-center">
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900">Can I install a sump pump myself to handle hydrostatic pressure?</h3>
                  <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-cyan-400 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                    <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                  </svg>
                </div>
              </button>
              <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6">
                <p class="text-slate-600">
                  While basic sump pump installation is possible for DIY, hydrostatic pressure requires comprehensive drainage systems with proper design, sizing, and integration. Improper installation can worsen problems, void insurance, and create safety hazards. Professional installation ensures proper capacity, redundancy, and compliance with building codes.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

